76561198056842200,Recommended,285050,29752021,Posted: 6 February,all,Nekouda,I like it. Well thought out. Great game to play when your watching a movie
,Recommended,285050,10258312,"Posted: 27 May, 2014",all,craigbic,"I came into Showtime! very skeptical after reading many of the reviews but was very pleasantly surprised to find an approachable and fun game with simple yet addictive mechanics. If you're an old movie buff or were a big fan of the Lionhead Studios game The Movies, than I think you will find a lot to like here.In the game, you are the head of your own movie studio. You can pick a starting date from 1927 up to 2013. As time passes bigger and better film and sound technology will become available to you but not always when you would expect it to (more about that later). You may choose the huge expense of upgrading to get the best possible quality for your movies or hang on to that outdated equipment to save a buck. You have a choice of buying existing scripts or hiring writers of various quality (indicated by star ranks and letter grades) to write original first drafts. Once written, scripts are rated for various categories such as pace, story arc, and characterization among others. The quality and experience of the writers in general as well as their ratings in these specific categories effects the quality of the script overall and for those categories. If you don't like the quality ratings of the script within a category or categoriesthen you can hire another writer to (preferably with better ratings than the one you hired before - at least for the problem categories) do a revision, a partial rewrite, or a total rewrite. Keep in mind, all of these take additional time. Once a script is ready, hire directors, actors (leading and supporting), and producers as needed. You may negotiate their contracts to help save money by tweaking the amount of up-front cash they receive and whether they get any percentage points of the gross film take. Actors can be assigned to direct or produce, directors to produce, and producers to direct all for the same salary to save additional cash at the expense, potentially, film quality. Once everyone is assigned their roles, you assign the production budget, special FX budget, CGI budget, hire stunt men and start filming. Random events can happen at anytime during the process such as writers needing additional time, actors dying by accident, tantrums, sickness, etc.. which is a nice touch and all of them  effect your production schedule. Once filming completes, you then set your films marketing and release budget and select whether to launch globally or to a limited market. Next you pick a release date and can even give your movie a custom movie poster from image files on your computer - which is a nice touch for those of us who like to REALLY get into a game and do a little RPG'ing. There is also a 7% revenue increase for movies with custom posters to act as an incentive to actually put one together, although I suppose you COULD use any old crummy image from your desktop instead of going through the bother of putting together mock movie posters(which is what I've been doing). After you launch, you either start raking in the dough or you start packing up for skid row. I'm glossing over the details for the sake of this review but there are a lot of variables that can effect the quality of your movie and the reception to it by the viewers.Where Lionhead's The Movies was very graphics oriented, Showtime! is very text driven. There are very few visuals and only a few basic sounds - not even background music as of now but what is there is enough to make the game compelling and addictive. There is more depth in the movie production process with Showtime! over Lionhead's The Movies which was much more about putting together actual 3D movies. The developer for Showtime! has gone the extra distance to put in some nice features such as the ability to pick custom movie posters for each of your movies, the ability to create movie sequels and start a film series complete with devoted fans - you can even sell the rights to a movie series if your studio is short of cash, long-term contract deals with talent, a movie hall of fame, and internal game achievements (although why this hasn't been worked into Steam achievements is beyond me - maybe down the road?).There are bugs and some odd time-period/linearity problems such as CGI being available in 1927 but the developer is very active with his community and seems to be right on top of getting our feedback and working it into regular updates along with all of the bug fixing.I do highly recommend this game if you're a fan of quirky mostly text-based games or old movies! It's very much worth the price and the developer is definitely continuing to work on improving it."
