76561198007761167,Recommended,285050,13819978,"Posted: 3 January, 2015",all,geozero,"SHOWTIME is one of those games that you can easily get into without a lot tutorials.  It's simplicity allows a lot replayability.  And you get your money's worth.  There are better games out there, THE MOVIES, but that is nearly 10 years old, and has lacked support.  It also bogs down as it tries to do too many things.  SHOWTIME on the other hand let's you run a studio and make films using siple controls.  The decisions seem to make some effect on the game, yet I was surprised that one of my sequels made a gazzilion dollars.I would like to see the following features:  Being able to start in 1920 with silent pictures and a smaller studio system, having verticle integration (i.e., buying, running and owning distribution channels AND theater chains), and being able to choose a HOME city and territory.Some things though seem to make little difference.  The city chose to make a film or some of the film or sound quality do not make much difference.  It would be great to automatically retain case and director on a re-make/sequel. Also would be great to see how many films a particular actor has been in (one actor I used was a low level actor, after the first film he jumped to A-List status demanding 30+ million dollars, so I assume he also made other films, since mine was a mediocre success).Other than that I think overall the game is worth it.  You will probably burn out after 2-3 hours.  But it's a game you can come back to later.  Because of this it is within what I would classify a THUMBS UP game."
